div.div:
The current simplistic query engine supports a `select where SVSpec` query iff there is an exact SI with the provided SVSpec.
1. Find the SI that has the SVSpec. If not found, fail.
2. Get range from the SI. Compare each (SV, PK) in index with user-provided SV. Return [ (PK, PV) ].
Note, whether the user query is for one SV or a range of SVs, it uses the SI API `get range`, not `get one`.

div.div:
We may design each secondary index to abstract any of:
a) SortedMap< SV, [ PV ] >
b) SortedMap< (SV, PK), Opt<PV> >
c) SortedMap< (SV, PK), Opt< (file path, file offset) > >
d) SortedMap< (SV, PK), Opt<()> >
a) K-merging in SI would be more complicated than in PI.
b) Aka "clustered index". Each PV is duplicated across all indexes (on disk and on memory).
c) Each SI SSTable entry does not duplicate PV, but points to a file offset within a PI SSTable. Range queries on SI require non-sequential disk read. Files' lifecycles must be managed carefully.
d) Client: 1) range-query SI to get [ PK ]; 2) query PI at individual PKs to get [ PV ]. This access pattern is equivalent to n+1 querying.
Current impl is b).

div.div:
Concurrency guarantees:
Option A: If each user query is run in its own thread:
- There is no isolation, not even Read Uncommitted.
- Rollbacks race with other writes.
Option B: If we remove support for transactions (e.g. RMW), then we would have Linearizable consistency.
Option C: If we run queries serially -- and hence have only 2 threads, a) queries executor, b) GC worker -- then we have Serializable isolation + Linearizable consistency.
Locking order:
To avoid deadlocks, always lock "top" mutex first, then "bottom" mutex (or always vice versa).
This design is not implemented.
